  "data": "{
  "query": "ISO-NE interconnection request tracking tool IRTT account registration customer ID CEII clearance requirements",
  "num_results": 5,
  "results": [
    {
      "url": "https://www.iso-ne.com/participate/applications-status-changes/interconnection-process-guide/register-for-an-irtt-account",
      "title": "Register for an IRTT Account",
      "author": "ISO New England",
      "text": "Register for an IRTT Account\n\n/isoexpress/webservices/-/webservice/getSignInInfo\n\n/isoexpress/webservices/-/webservice/authenticate\n\n# Register for an IRTT Account\n\n### In this section\n\n- Interconnection Process Guide\n- Is the ISO New England Interconnection Process Right for You?\n- Register for an IRTT Account\n- Submit an Interconnection Request During Cluster Request Window\n- Register Your Asset\n\nAfter you’ve confirmed that the ISO New England interconnection process applies to your project, you will then need to request an ISO customer ID and access to restricted Interconnection Request (IR) critical energy infrastructure information (CEII).\n\nOn this page:\n\n- Request an ISO Customer ID\n- Request Access to Restricted Critical Energy Infrastructure Information\n- Create an Account in ISO New England’s Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT)\n\n- Governing Documents\n- Questions\n\nIf you haven’t already done so, you must complete the following steps before you can submit an IR:\n\n## Request an ISO Customer ID\n\nComplete and submit the Request Generation Interconnect Customer ID to get an ISO customer ID. If you already have an ISO customer ID, you’ll use that ID and your customer name as it appears in the Customer Asset Management System (CAMS) database. Note: The ISO customer ID name must match across all ISO registrations, submissions, and systems.\n\n## Request Access to Restricted Critical Energy Infrastructure Information\n\nSubmit a request to access restricted Interconnection Request (IR) critical energy infrastructure information because you’ll need to provide and view restricted CEII as part of the interconnection process. After the ISO has approved your IR CEII access (Follow the instructions for requesting access to the appropriate CEII materials), it will issue you a digital certificate.\n\n## Create an Account in ISO New England’s Interconnection Request Tracking Tool\n\nThe web-based Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT) is used to submit requests to interconnect proposed generators or elective transmission upgrades (ETUs) or upgrades to existing generators or ETUs, to submit required documentation, and to monitor the progress of your interconnection request. You will need to complete the IRTT request account process:\n\n- Customers can register for an account on the IRTT page. See how to create accounts in the Interconnection Request Tracking Tool for more details.\n- If you aren’t an ISO customer yet, see the New Customer Registration page for guidance on establishing a relationship with the ISO. Once this relationship is established, you can create a company in the Interconnection Request Tracking Tool.\n\n## Governing Documents\n\nThe interconnection process rules are detailed in the ISO’s Open Access Transmission Tariff(OATT). See the applicable schedule:\n\n- Schedule 22, Large Generator Interconnection Procedures\n- Schedule 23, Small Generator Interconnection Procedures\n- Schedule 25, Elective Transmission Upgrade Interconnection Procedures\n\n## Questions?\n\nEmail IRTT Participant Support at irtt@iso-ne.com, or contact ISO Participant Support.\n\nNext step: Submit an Interconnection Request",
      "highlights": [
        "After you’ve confirmed that the ISO New England interconnection process applies to your project, you will then need to request an ISO customer ID and access to restricted Interconnection Request (IR) critical energy infrastructure information (CEII).\n[...]\nan IR:\n[...]\n## Request an ISO Customer ID\n[...]\nComplete and submit the Request Generation Interconnect Customer ID to get an ISO customer ID. If you already have an ISO customer ID, you’ll use that ID and your customer name as it appears in the Customer Asset Management System (CAMS) database. Note: The ISO customer ID name must match across all ISO registrations, submissions, and systems.\n[...]\n## Request Access to Restricted Critical Energy Infrastructure Information\n[...]\nSubmit a request to access restricted Interconnection Request (IR) critical energy infrastructure information because you’ll need to provide and view restricted CEII as part of the interconnection process. After the ISO has approved your IR CEII access (Follow the instructions for requesting access to the appropriate CEII materials), it will issue you a digital certificate.\n[...]\n## Create an Account in ISO New England’s Interconnection Request Tracking Tool\n[...]\nThe web-based Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT) is used to submit requests to interconnect proposed generators or elective transmission upgrades (ETUs) or upgrades to existing generators or ETUs, to submit required documentation, and to monitor the progress of your interconnection request. You will need to complete the IRTT request account process:\n[...]\n- Customers can register for an account on the IRTT page. See how to create accounts in the Interconnection Request Tracking Tool for more details.\n- If you aren’t an ISO customer yet, see the New Customer Registration page for guidance on establishing a relationship with the ISO. Once this relationship is established, you can create a company in the Interconnection Request Tracking Tool."
      ]
    },
    {
      "url": "https://irtt.iso-ne.com/account/preregister",
      "title": "ISO New England Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT)",
      "text": "ISO-New England IRTT ;\n\n# ISO New England Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT)\n\n## Pre Account Registration\n\n---\n\n### IRTT - CEII Request Form\n\nCritical Energy Infrastructure Information (CEII)\n\nTo request CEII, download the CEII Request form using the link below. CEII Request Form\n\n### IRTT - ISO NE Customer ID Form\n\nCustomer Information for GI Studies Billing\n\nTo request an ISO NE Customer ID, download the request form using the link below. ISO NE Customer ID Request Form\n\nHave you submitted a CEII Request form to ISO New England?\n\nYes No\n\nHave you submitted an NDA form to ISO New England?\n\nYes No\n\nHave you submitted an ISO Customer ID request form?\n\nYes No",
      "highlights": [
        "ISO-New England IRTT ;\n\n# ISO New England Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT)\n\n## Pre Account Registration\n\n---\n\n### IRTT - CEII Request Form\n\nCritical Energy Infrastructure Information (CEII)\n\nTo request CEII, download the CEII Request form using the link below. CEII Request Form\n\n### IRTT - ISO NE Customer ID Form\n\nCustomer Information for GI Studies Billing\n\nTo request an ISO NE Customer ID, download the request form using the link below. ISO NE Customer ID Request Form\n\nHave you submitted a CEII Request form to ISO New England?\n\nYes No\n\nHave you submitted an NDA form to ISO New England?\n\nYes No\n\nHave you submitted an ISO Customer ID request form?\n\nYes No"
      ]
    },
    {
      "url": "https://www.iso-ne.com/participate/applications-status-changes/interconnection-process-guide/submit-an-interconnection-request",
      "title": "Submit an Interconnection Request During Cluster Request Window",
      "author": "ISO New England",
      "text": "Submit an Interconnection Request During Cluster Request Window\n\n/isoexpress/webservices/-/webservice/getSignInInfo\n\n/isoexpress/webservices/-/webservice/authenticate\n\n# Submit an Interconnection Request During Cluster Request Window\n\n### In this section\n\n- Interconnection Process Guide\n- Is the ISO New England Interconnection Process Right for You?\n- Register for an IRTT Account\n- Submit an Interconnection Request During Cluster Request Window\n- Register Your Asset\n\n### Related Links\n\n- Glossary of Interconnection-Related Acronyms\n- Interconnection-Related Governing Documents\n- Contact IRTT Support\n\nOnce you’ve confirmed that your project is eligible for ISO New England’s interconnection process and you’ve received a customer ID, obtained Interconnection Request (IR) critical energy infrastructure information (CEII) clearance, and created an account in the Interconnection Request Tracking System (IRTT), you’re ready to submit an interconnection request (IR) during the 45 calendar day Cluster Request Window.\n\nOn this page:\n\n- Do Sufficient Research\n- Select Type of Interconnection Service\n- Submit Your Interconnection Request\n\n- Register for Market Participation\n- Questions?\n\n## Prepare for Next Cluster Request Window\n\nTo ensure success during the Interconnection Process, please review the information below:\n\n- Check the ISO Interconnection Request Queue for other projects already proposed in the area where you’re planning to interconnect. You may find completed analyses for these projects useful—see the Interconnection Request Studies page (IR CEII required).\n- Study the interconnection materials that apply to your project—look for the applicable ISO Tariff schedule in the table below.\n- Carefully review all technical requirements for each study before submitting an interconnection request. Planning Procedure No. 5-6 (PP 5-6), Interconnection Planning Procedure for Generation and Elective Transmission Upgrades, describes the scope and assumptions of interconnection studies. Operating Procedure 14 (OP-14), Technical Requirements For Generators, Demand-Response Resources, Asset-Related Demands, and Alternative Technology Regulation Resources, identifies requirements that help ensure the reliable and efficient operation of market resources.\n- Use public information, such as FERC Form No. 715, Annual Transmission Planning and Evaluation Reports(IR CEII required), to do your own preliminary analysis of the system. Look for special considerations, such as weak grid issues, that could impact your project.\n\n## Decide on Type of Interconnection Service\n\nYour IR must indicate the type of interconnection service your project requests:\n\n- Network resource (NR) or network import (NI) interconnection service (energy capability only)—This enables participation in all energy markets, except the capacity market. If later you wish to participate in the capacity market, you’ll have to submit a new interconnection request for capacity network interconnection service.\n- Capacity network resource (CNR) or capacity network import (CNI) interconnection service (energy capability and capacity capability)—This enables participation in the energy and capacity markets. For more information, see the qualification process for generators and imports associated with elective transmission upgrades (ETUs).\n\n## Questions?\n\nEmail IRTT Participant Support at irtt@iso-ne.com, or contact ISO Participant Support.\n\nPrevious step: Register for an IRTT Account",
      "highlights": [
        "- Interconnection Process Guide\n- Is the ISO New England Interconnection Process Right for You?\n- Register for an IRTT Account\n- Submit an Interconnection Request During Cluster Request Window\n- Register Your Asset\n[...]\nOnce you’ve confirmed that your project is eligible for ISO New England’s interconnection process and you’ve received a customer ID, obtained Interconnection Request (IR) critical energy infrastructure information (CEII) clearance, and created an account in the Interconnection Request Tracking System (IRTT), you’re ready to submit an interconnection request (IR) during the 45 calendar day Cluster Request Window.\n[...]\n- Check the ISO Interconnection Request Queue for other projects already proposed in the area where you’re planning to interconnect. You may find completed analyses for these projects useful—see the Interconnection Request Studies page (IR CEII required).\n[...]\n- Carefully review all technical requirements for each study before submitting an interconnection request. Planning Procedure No. 5-6 (PP 5-6), Interconnection Planning Procedure for Generation and Elective Transmission Upgrades, describes the scope and assumptions of interconnection studies. Operating Procedure 14 (OP-14), Technical Requirements For Generators, Demand-Response Resources, Asset-Related Demands, and Alternative Technology Regulation Resources, identifies requirements that help ensure the reliable and efficient operation of market resources.\n[...]\n- Use public information, such as FERC Form No. 715, Annual Transmission Planning and Evaluation Reports(IR CEII required), to do your own preliminary analysis of the system. Look for special considerations, such as weak grid issues, that could impact your project.\n[...]\nthe type of\n[...]\nEmail IRTT Participant Support at irtt@iso-ne.com, or contact ISO Participant Support.\n[...]\nPrevious step: Register for an IRTT Account"
      ]
    },
    {
      "url": "https://www.iso-ne.com/participate/applications-status-changes/interconnection-process-guide",
      "title": "Interconnection Process Guide",
      "author": "ISO New England",
      "text": "Interconnection Process Guide\n\n/isoexpress/webservices/-/webservice/getSignInInfo\n\n/isoexpress/webservices/-/webservice/authenticate\n\n# Interconnection Process Guide\n\n### In this section\n\n- Interconnection Process Guide\n- Is the ISO New England Interconnection Process Right for You?\n- Register for an IRTT Account\n- Submit an Interconnection Request During Cluster Request Window\n- Register Your Asset\n\n### Related Links\n\n- Glossary of Interconnection-Related Acronyms\n- Interconnection-Related Governing Documents\n- Contact IRTT Support\n\nISO New England is providing this web guide to assist you in understanding the interconnection process for small and large generating facilities and elective transmission upgrades (ETUs) to interconnect to the administered transmission system. However, you shouldn’t rely solely on this web guide. Consult the ISO New England Inc. Transmission, Markets, and Services Tariff(ISO Tariff), Section II, known as the ISO’s Open Access Transmission Tariff(OATT), and relevant planning procedures and operating procedures to ensure that you are complying with all requirements. In case of any discrepancy with this web guide, the ISO Tariff and applicable operating procedures and planning procedures govern.\n\n## Overview of the Interconnection Process\n\nAs a Regional Transmission Organization (RTO), the ISO coordinates how transmission lines, power plants, and other resources connect to and operate on New England’s administered transmission system to ensure reliability and facilitate wholesale electricity market participation. The ISO does not administer the interconnection process for projects subject to state interconnection processes. Thus, after you determine that the ISO interconnection process applies to your project, you’ll need to submit an interconnection request to the ISO through the Interconnection Request Tracking Tool(IRTT). Existing customers can register for an account using IRTT, while new customers must first or simultaneously obtain an ISO customer ID and access to critical energy infrastructure information.\n\nAs required by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission’s Order No. 2023, it is only possible to submit interconnection requests during a cluster request window. The next window to submit a complete interconnection request package for the next Cluster Study is expected to be open from October 5, 2026 to November 19, 2026. After the ISO validates your interconnection request and the cluster request window closes, the customer engagement window opens and a cluster study scoping meeting is held. A cluster study scoping meeting will address pertinent information about your project and the interconnection studies the ISO will perform to assess your project’s impact on the power system and the facilities and upgrades potentially needed to interconnect your project per all requirements and standards.\n\nAfter the ISO has completed the necessary study work, you’ll work with the ISO and the transmission owner on an Interconnection Agreement (IA), a formal document detailing the terms and conditions for interconnection service. You must enter into an IA before you can construct or operate a generator or an elective transmission upgrade. Final steps of the interconnection process are to submit final data and register your asset with the ISO.\n\n## Governing Documents\n\nSeveral schedules of the ISO’s Open Access Transmission Tariff contain the rules detailing the interconnection process:\n\nSection II, ISO New England Open Access Transmission Tariff(OATT)\n\n- Helps ensure that all transmission owners and transmission customers have open access to transmission service in New England\n- Details the rights and responsibilities of transmission owners and transmission customers as well as the procedures they must follow and the fees transmission customers must pay to access the transmission system\n- Sets out the transmission system planning process for the region\n\n## Resources and Tools\n\n- ISO Planning Procedure No. 5-6(PP 5-6), Scope of Study for System Impact Studies under the Generation Interconnection Procedures—describes the scope of interconnection studies conducted pursuant to Schedule 22, Schedule 23, and Schedule 25.\n- For additional resources for the Interconnection Process see Interconnection Service.\n- “Interconnection Process” training is available on the Training Materials webpage.\n- See the IRTT public queue. (Log in not necessary.) For information on the public version of the ISO New England Interconnection (ISO Queue), visit the Interconnection Request Queue webpage.\n- See the ISO Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT) and IRTT User Guide.\n- See the Interconnection Request Studies page to view completed studies for projects listed in the ISO’s Interconnection Request Queue (IR CEII required to view).\n- Interconnection frequently asked questions can be found in Ask ISO.\n- See Order No. 2023 Key Project page to access documents and resources related to the Order No. 2023: Improvements to Generator Interconnection Procedures and Agreements.\n- Read ISO-NE’s September 30, 2025, responses to Order Nos. 2023/2023-A transition-related questions\n- Read the Interconnection Request Technical Data Submittal Guidance document for guidance on submitting the technical data required for a Cluster Study.\n\n## Questions\n\nEmail IRTT Participant Support at irtt@iso-ne.com, or contact ISO Participant Support.\n\n## Interconnection Documents\n\n### Filters\n\nFilter this list ↑\n\n### Documents\n\n| A listing of links to documents. | Title and Description | Date | Type | Size |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n\nSorry, no results are available with this choice of filter(s). Please deselect one or more filters.",
      "highlights": [
        "- Is the ISO New England\n[...]\n- Register for an IRTT Account\n[...]\n- Submit an Interconnection Request During Cluster Request Window\n- Register Your Asset\n[...]\nAs a Regional Transmission Organization (RTO), the ISO coordinates how transmission lines, power plants, and other resources connect to and operate on New England’s administered transmission system to ensure reliability and facilitate wholesale electricity market participation. The ISO does not administer the interconnection process for projects subject to state interconnection processes. Thus, after you determine that the ISO interconnection process applies to your project, you’ll need to submit an interconnection request to the ISO through the Interconnection Request Tracking Tool(IRTT). Existing customers can register for an account using IRTT, while new customers must first or simultaneously obtain an ISO customer ID and access to critical energy infrastructure information.\n[...]\nby the Federal\n[...]\nRegulatory Commission’s Order No. 20\n[...]\n3, it is only possible to submit\n[...]\nduring a cluster request window. The next window to submit a complete\n[...]\nrequest package for the next Cluster Study is expected to be open from October\n[...]\n5, 2\n[...]\nand the cluster request window closes, the\n[...]\nwindow opens and a cluster study scoping meeting is held. A\n[...]\nstudy scoping meeting will address pertinent information\n[...]\nsystem and the facilities and upgrades potentially needed to\n[...]\nyour project per all requirements and standards.\n[...]\n- See the IRTT public queue. (Log in not necessary.) For information on the public version of the ISO New England Interconnection (ISO\n[...]\n), visit the Interconnection Request Queue webpage.\n[...]\n- See the ISO Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT) and IRTT User Guide.\n[...]\n- See the Interconnection Request Studies page to view completed studies for projects listed in the ISO’s Interconnection Request Queue (IR CEII required to view)."
      ]
    },
    {
      "url": "https://www.iso-ne.com/static-assets/documents/support/user_guides/irtt_user_guide.pdf",
      "title": "[PDF] Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT) - User Guide",
      "text": "ISO-NE PUBLIC\n\n##### Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT) User Guide\n\n© ISO New England Inc. Version 4 .0\n\n## September 2022\n\nISO-NE PUBLIC\n\nTable of Contents\n\nChange Summary ... 4 \nOverview ... 5 \nIntroduction ... 5 \nTechnical Requirements ... 6 \nParticipant Support ... 6 \nInterconnection Request Tracking Tool ... 7 \nIRTT User Interface ... 7 \nHome Page ... 8 \nStatus Area ... 8 \nDashboard ... 8 \nCompany Requests ... 10 \nIndividual Requests ... 10 \nAccount Management ... 11 \nRoles ... 11 \nCreating an IRTT Company Admin Account ... 11 \nCreating New User Accounts ... 14 \nAdding an Existing User to a Related Company ... 16 \nNew User Confirmation and Log In ... 17 \nConfirming Your IRTT Account ... 17 \nSigning in to IRTT ... 18 \nManaging Settings ... 19 \nViewing Account Details ... 19 \nModifying Account Details ... 20 \nRemoving a User Account ... 21 \nChanging Your Password ... 22 \nResetting a Lost Password ... 24 \nModifying a User Account Role ... 26 \nManaging Access to Interconnection Requests ... 27 \nCommunications ... 28 \nManaging the Primary Representative of an Interconnection Request ... 28 \nManaging Companies ... 29 \nCreating a Subsidiary Company ... 29 \nAdding an Existing Subsidiary Company ... 31 \nRemoving a Subsidiary Company ... 32 \nSubmitting Interconnection Requests ... 33 \nSubmitting a Large Generator Request ... 33 \nProject Information Tab ... 34 \nUploads Tab ... 35 \n\nISO-NE PUBLIC\n\nAttachments to IR Tab ... 36 \nSignature Tab ... 39 \nSubmitting the Request ... 41 \nSubmitting a Small Generator Request ... 43 \nProject Information Tab ... 43 \nAttachments to IR Tab ... 45 \nGeneral and Upload Tabs ... 50 \nSignature Tab ... 52 \nSubmitting the Request ... 53 \nSubmitting an Elective Transmission Upgrade (ETU) Interconnection Request ... 55 \nProject Information Tab ... 55 \nAttachments to IR Tab ... 57 \nUploads and Signature Tabs ... 59 \nSubmitting the Request ... 62 \nSubmitting a Surplus Interconnection Service Request ... 64 \nProject Information Tab ... 64 \nUploads Tab ... 65 \nSignature Tab ... 66 \nSubmitting the Request ... 67 \nEditing or Curing Interconnection Requests ... 69 \nModifying a Draft Interconnection Request ... 69 \nModifying a Locked Interconnection Request ... 70 \nAttachments and Locked Requests ... 70 \nSubmitting Supplemental Information ... 72 \nUploads and Locked Requests ... 72 \nChanging Project Information for an Interconnection Request ... 74 \nCuring a Deficient Interconnection Request ... 76 \nViewing Interconnection Requests ... 78 \nViewing an Interconnection Request ... 78 \nViewing a Summary of Interconnection Requests ... 79 \nViewing Uploads for an Interconnection Request ... 80 \nExporting an Interconnection Request ... 81 \nInterconnection Requests Form Templates ... 83 \nViewing the Public Queue ... 84 \nAppendix ... 86 \nFunctions Available to Roles ... 86 \nHelpful Links ... 87 \n\n#### Change Summary\n\nRevision Date Comments \nVersion 1.0 May 31, 2013 Initial release \nVersion 2.0 December 23, 2014 Updated for recently FERC \napproved Schedule 23 changes, \nand additional system \nenhancements \nVersion 3.0 2017 Updated to reflect new IRTT \nimplementation / user \ninterfaces \nVersion 4.0 2022 Updated to reflect revised \ninterface \n\n### Overview\n\n#### Introduction\n\nThis user guide provides details for the system used by ISO New England to track Large and Small Generator \nInterconnection Requests, Surplus Interconnection Service Requests, and Elective Transmission Upgrade \nInterconnection Requests. Do not use this guide for requirements as the Market Rule and Manuals serve \nthat function. \nThe procedures for Large and Small Generator interconnection can be found in Schedules 22 and 23, \nrespectively, of the Open Access Transmission Tariff (OATT), Section II of the Transmission, Markets and \nServices Tariff (Tariff). The procedures for Elective Transmission Upgrade interconnection can be found in \nSchedules 25 of the Open Access Transmission Tariff, Section II of the Transmission, Markets and Services \nTariff (Tariff). \nCustomers are encouraged to review the relevant governing language in Section II of the Tariff prior to \nusing IRTT to submit interconnection requests: \n• The ISO New England Inc. Transmission, Markets and Services Tariff (“Tariff”) at: http://www.iso ne.com/participate/rules-procedures/tariff o Section I – General Terms and Conditions  Section I.2.2 – Definitions o Section II – Open Access Transmission Tariff o Section II. Schedule 22 – Standard Large Generator Interconnection Procedures o Section II. Schedule 23 – Standard Small Generator Interconnection Procedures o Section II. Schedule 25 – Elective Transmission Upgrade Interconnection Procedures \n• The relevant supporting documentation for new or modified interconnections on the ISO New England website at: http://www.iso-ne.com/participate/applications-status-changes/new modified-interconnections Use this guide as a reference for completing tasks or understanding functions such as: \n• Creating and managing accounts \n• Submitting an interconnection request \n• Granting access to an interconnection request \n• Viewing and curing existing interconnection requests Please note that while we attempt to keep this guide current, the screen shots in this guide may not fully reflect the current production environment. \n\nTechnical Requirements\n\nThe IRTT application requires the following:\n\n• Microsoft Edge and Google Chrome are the supported browsers. Refer to the Web Browser Support for SMD Applications page of our website for additional details on the browsers and security protocols ISO New England supports. You can find this page under Participate > Support > Web Browser Support. \n• The ISO New England Application Portal used to access IRTT requires the Java Runtime Environment (JRE), version 1.5 (or higher). \n• Users will be prompted to install the Unified Access Gateway Plug-in or Java Applet the first time they visit the ISO New England Application Portal. \n• Please work with your company’s desktop or IT support first to ensure the minimum requirements have been met. If additional support is needed, please contact ISO New England’s Participant Support. \n\n#### Participant Support\n\nYou can reach participant support using the following methods:\n\n• Internet: https://www.iso-ne.com/participate/support \n• Telephone: During regular business hours, Monday through Friday 8:00 A.M. to 5:00 P.M. Eastern Time (413) 540-4220 or (833) 248-4220 o Days of Operation: The Customer Support Hotline is NOT staffed on the following days:  New Year's Day  Martin Luther King Day  Presidents Day  Memorial Day  Independence Day  Labor Day  Thanksgiving Day  Day After Thanksgiving  Christmas Eve Afternoon (12:00 to 17:30)  Christmas Day o For emergency inquiries by pager: (877) 226-4814 \n• Email: askiso@iso-ne.com or memcoord@iso-ne.com \n• Ask ISO: Ask ISO is available to market participants who have a valid digital certificate and who have been assigned the role of “Ask ISO / External User” by their Security Administrator. Ask ISO is located at https://askiso.force.com. \n\n### Interconnection Request Tracking Tool\n\nThe Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT) is ISO New England’s tracking tool for Large Generator \nInterconnection Requests, Small Generator Interconnection Requests, and Elective Transmission upgrades \n(ETU) Interconnection Requests. IRTT is used by interconnection customers for submittal and by ISO New \nEngland for review and approval of interconnection requests. \nNote: IRTT automatically logs you out after 10 minutes of inactivity \n\n#### IRTT User Interface\n\nThe IRTT interface is organized by a persistent navigation menu displayed on the left side of the IRTT page. \nThe selected menu item determines what displays in the viewing area. \n\nThe menu items expand into sub-menus providing access to create, view, or edit IRTT information. The availability of menu items and their functions vary depending on your user account role. The top level menu contains:\n\n• Help Por",
      "highlights": [
        "11\n[...]\nCreating an IRTT Company Admin Account ... 11\n[...]\nCreating New User Accounts ... 14\n[...]\nNew User Confirmation and Log In ... 17\n[...]\nConfirming Your IRTT Account ... 17\n[...]\nSigning in to IRTT ... 18\n[...]\nViewing Account Details ...\n[...]\n19\n[...]\n• Creating and managing accounts \n• Submitting an interconnection request \n• Granting access to an interconnection request \n• Viewing and curing existing interconnection requests Please note that while we attempt to keep this guide current, the screen shots in this guide may not fully reflect the current production environment. \n\nTechnical Requirements\n[...]\nThe IRTT application requires the following:\n[...]\n• Microsoft Edge and Google Chrome are the supported browsers. Refer to the Web Browser Support for SMD Applications page of our website for additional details on the browsers and security protocols ISO New England supports. You can find this page under Participate > Support > Web Browser Support.\n[...]\n• The ISO New England Application Portal used to access IRTT requires the Java Runtime Environment (JRE), version 1.5 (or higher). \n• Users will be prompted to install the Unified Access Gateway Plug-in or Java Applet the first time they visit the ISO New England Application Portal.\n[...]\n• Please work with your company’s desktop or IT support first to ensure the minimum requirements have been met. If additional support is needed, please contact ISO New England’s Participant Support.\n[...]\nThe Interconnection Request Tracking Tool (IRTT) is ISO New England’s tracking tool for Large Generator \nInterconnection Requests, Small Generator Interconnection Requests, and Elective Transmission upgrades \n(ETU) Interconnection Requests. IRTT is used by interconnection customers for submittal and by ISO New \nEngland for review and approval of interconnection requests. \nNote: IRTT automatically logs you out after 10 minutes of inactivity \n\n#### IRTT User Interface"
