      "text": "NEPOOL TRANSMISSION COMMITTEE | MAY 22, 2025 | WESTBOROUGH, MA\n\nAlex Rost\n\nFurther Compliance Revisions\n\nOrder No. 2023/2023-A (Rev. 1)\n\nDIRECTOR | TRANSMISSION SERVICES\n\nProject Title: Orders No. 2023 and 2023-A Further Compliance Revisions\n\nProposed Effective Date: August 12, 2024 (i.e., effective date accepted in April 4, 2025 order)\n\n• FERC issued an order on New England’s Orders No. 2023 and 2023-A Compliance Proposal on April 4, 2025 – While the April 4, 2025 order largely accepted the Compliance Proposal, the order directed submission of a further compliance filing within 60 days of the order (i.e., June 3, 2025) – On May 2, 2025, the ISO, joined by NEPOOL and the PTO AC, filed narrowly tailored Tariff revisions to modify dates associated with the Order No. 2023 transition process from 2024 to 2025 \n• This presentation reviews the ISO’s proposed Tariff revisions in response to the Compliance Order – Revisions include changes to Schedules 11, 22, 23, and 25 of the OATT and Section I.2.2 of the Tariff, as well as a correction to Section III.13 – Expeditious action is required to allow for a June 3, 2025 filing – Accordingly, the Transmission Committee is being asked to take action on these proposed Tariff revisions at today’s meeting* * The NEPOOL Markets Committee Chair and Vice-Chair have been consulted on the minor change to Section III.13 to ensure that the Commission-approved language is reflected in the posted version of the Tariff and no further action is required, as outlined in the memo \n\nAPRIL 4, 2025 ORDER\n\nOverview of further compliance requirements\n\nSummary of April 4, 2025 Order\n\n• At a high level, the April 4, 2025 order: – Accepts the main components of the Compliance Proposal, including the major deviations from the FERC pro forma rules proposed under the independent entity variation – Directs further compliance to 1) correct errors or 2) address minor deviations that warrant further justification or correction* – Did not modify the June 13, 2024 eligibility date set by Order No. 2023 and affirmed in Order No. 2023-A – Accepts all dates proposed in the Compliance Proposal, including the August 12, 2024 effective date \n• This effective date sets the effective date for the further compliance revisions *Note that while the Compliance Order did not direct changes to conform Schedules 23 and 25 with Schedule 22 in all instances, the ISO proposes changes across all three schedules to ensure consistent rules where appropriate \n\nIntroduced at April TC\n\nPROPOSED FURTHER COMPLIANCE TARIFF REVISIONS\n\nOverview of Tariff revisions to meet further compliance requirements of the Compliance Order\n\n| Tariff Section(s) | Order Paragraph/Requirement | Compliance Path |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Schedules 22/23/25 – Section 3.4.4 | P 77 – Adopt the pro forma LGIP section 3.4.4 language that “[a]t any time, if Transmission Provider finds that the technical data provided by Interconnection Customer is incomplete or contains errors, Interconnection Customer and Transmission Provider shall work expeditiously and in good faith to remedy such issues” | Propose to adopt this language |\n| Schedules 22/23/25 – Section 4.4 | P 77 – Adopt the pro forma language in section 4.4 re: modifications to a POI only being allowed to take place prior to the start of the Cluster Study | Propose to further justify current Tariff language allowing POI changes at any time during a Cluster Study; This approach allows for flexibility and less Cluster attrition |\n| Schedules 22/23/25 – Sections 5.1.1, 5.1.1.1, 7.2 | P 77, 186 – Remove proposed deviations stating that failure to cure would result in withdrawal without cure period provided under Section 3.7 of this LGIP | Propose to remove this language |\n\nFurther Compliance Tariff Revisions\n\nRev. 1\n\n| Tariff Section(s) | Order Paragraph/Requirement | Compliance Path |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Schedules 22/23/25 – Sections 4.2.2, 4.2.3.1.2, 4.2.3.2 | P 85 – Provide details regarding IRs required to take part in a CRPS, including: the timeline for interconnection customers who submit an IR and are subsequently informed that they must participate in a CETU study process; whether ISO-NE will either refund interconnection study-related deposits or maintain them through the CETU study process; and whether the commercial operation dates submitted as part of an IR that moves to the CETU study process will be extended or revised | Proposed to include language in Tariff revisions to clarify these requirements |\n| Schedules 22/23/25, Section I.2.2 – Definitions | P 100 – Adopt the pro forma definition of “proportional impact method.” | Propose to conform definition in Schedules 22/23/25; Added definition to Section I.2.2 since term proposed for use in Schedule 11 |\n| Schedule 11 – 5(ii)(1)(b)(ii) | Section P 102 – Describe the proportional impact method used for other non-CETU system network upgrade types (including but not limited to system network upgrades comprising reactive devices or substation additions beyond the point of interconnection) | Propose to revise consistent with Order No. 2023 recommended language and PP5-6 as presented to NEPOOL and supported by stakeholders in 2024 |\n\nFurther Compliance Tariff Revisions (cont'd)\n\n| Tariff Section(s) | Order Paragraph/Requirement | Compliance Path |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Schedules 22/23 – LGIA and SGIA Definitions | P 133 – Adopt the revised pro forma definition of “generating facility” | Propose to revise definition to correct error |\n| Schedules 22/23/25 – Definitions | P 135 – Define regulatory limitations, publicly post the definition, and provide a narrative description of how they define regulatory limitations, or justify the proposal under the independent entity variation standard | Propose to define consistent with Order No. 2023; ISO will provide further narrative on its website ahead of filing the revisions; Will also correct Schedule 25 Section 3.3.2 to include Regulatory Limitation Site Control language |\n| Schedules 22/23/25 – Section 3.4.2 | P 152 – Adopt the pro forma LGIP section 3.4.2 language that a commercial readiness deposit may be in an “other form of security reasonably acceptable to Transmission Provider” or justify the proposal under the independent entity variation standard | Propose to not to include this language and justify as an independent entity variation (IEV); Multiple deposit options now exist, and in-process evaluations of other options likely will cause procedural complexity |\n\nFurther Compliance Tariff Revisions (cont'd)\n\n| Tariff Section(s) | Order Paragraph/Requirement | Compliance Path |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Schedules 22/23/25 – LGIA, SGIA and ETU IA Article 11.5 | P 158 – Adopt the full article 11.5 of the pro forma LGIA on use of previously provided LGIA/SGIA/ETU IA deposits before requiring additional security | Propose to include language previously excluded without further deviation |\n| Schedules 22/23/25 – Attachment A to Appendix 3 | P 197 – Eliminate reasonable efforts standards language or justify as an IEV | Propose to remove language inadvertently included |\n| Schedules 22/23/25 – Section 9.6 | P 218 – Include word “report,” which was omitted from the second to last sentence | Propose to include language |\n\nFurther Compliance Tariff Revisions (cont'd)\n\n| Tariff Section(s) | Order Paragraph/Requirement | Compliance Path |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Schedules 22/23/25 – Appendices 9 and 10 – Section 3.2.2 (Repayment) | P 227 – Section 3.2.2 was omitted from Appendix 10; double references were included to Interconnecting Transmission Owner | Propose to correct references Propose as IEV to remove Section 3.2.2 from Appendices 9 and 10 because the ISO-NE Tariff does not provide for repayment, and language was included in Appendix 10 in Compliance Proposal in error |\n| Schedule 23 – Article – 1.5.7 | SGIA P 280 – Adopt pro forma language stating that the control and protection settings of small generating facilities are configured or set to continu",
