      "text": "ISO-NE Responses to Order Nos. 2023/2023-A Transition Related Questions\n\nSeptember 30, 2025\n\nGeneral Notes Applicable to the ISO-NE Responses There is overlap between many of the questions received by ISO-NE in the context of Order No. 2023. Not all questions received by ISO-NE are documented below, but the questions and answers documented below attempt to provide responses to all received questions.\n\nThe responses in this document reflect ISO-NE’s views of, and expected compliance with, Order Nos. 2023 and 2023-A at the time of its publication. These ISO-NE views and compliance expectations may change depending on FERC’s response to ISO-NE’s currently pending Order No. 2023 further compliance filing, or as ISO-NE continues to work through Order No. 2023 implementation. Participants should continually check for updates and review the final version of the rules.\n\nQuestions and Responses\n\nQ1: Can a project withdraw without penalty prior to October 10, 2025?\n\nResponse: Yes, see Section 5.1.1 of the Schedule 22, 23 and 25 on the Open Access Transmission Tariff (OATT) page.\n\nQ2: When will ISO-NE start the process of issuing a refund for any unused funds paid for the feasibility study or system impact study for projects that do not have a completed system impact study?\n\nResponse: Any unused balance of the feasibility study deposit or system impact study deposit associated with the Interconnection Request (IR) may be applied toward the study deposit associated with the Transitional Cluster Study (TCS) for projects that execute a TCS Agreement. If what remains of the feasibility study deposit or system impact study deposit is more than the amount necessary for the TCS study deposit, then the excess would be refunded. If the project does not proceed with the TCS and is withdrawn, any unspent study deposit amount will be refunded.\n\nQ3: When will ISO-NE review TCS data (including technical data)?\n\nResponse: Beginning August 11, 2025 and through October 10, 2025, ISO-NE will review data submitted as part of a fully executed TCS Agreement package for completeness and notify the Interconnection Customer (IC) if they are missing any components of the data package submitted. Please note that submissions received close to the October 10 th deadline are not guaranteed to be reviewed by ISO-NE for completeness before the TCS Agreement submission deadline. ISO-NE cannot further review data (including technical data) submitted as part of a fully executed TCS Agreement package for deficiencies until the start of the TCS (i.e., October 11, 2025). After the start of the TCS, ISO-NE will notify the IC if any data deficiencies are found, at which point the project will be subject to Section 3.7 of Schedule 22 and 23 of the OATT, and Section 3.6 of Schedule 25 of the OATT. ISO-NE will not review data before submission of a fully executed TCS Agreement.\n\nQ4: Can data deficiencies be cured after October 10, 2025?\n\nResponse: If the IC provides a fully executed TCS Agreement, required deposits, proof of site control, and modelling data (i.e., a fully executed TCS Agreement package), and then, during the TCS ISO-NE identifies a deficiency with data at any time thereafter, ISO-NE will notify the project’s IC of the deficiency and that the project will be withdrawn pursuant to Section 3.7 of Schedules 22 and 23 or Section 3.6 of Schedule 25. Pursuant to these Tariff sections, the project’s IC will then have 15 Business Days to respond with information or actions to cure the deficiency pursuant to those sections.\n\nQ5: What version of ISO-NE Planning Procedure 5-6 will apply to the technical data submitted as part of a fully executed TCS Agreement, and to the TCS?\n\nResponse: ICs must meet the technical data requirements in effect at the time a technical data submission is required, including those contained in PP5-6. As such, all Interconnection Customers that submit new or revised technical data are required to comply with requirements in the currently effective PP5-6 for the TCS, including Appendix C-1.*\n\nRevision 13 of PP5-6 will be the effective version of PP5-6 through the October 10, 2025 TCS Agreement submission deadline. The version of PP5-6 updated for Order No. 2023 Cluster Studies will be used for the TCS, and will be made effective on or soon after October 11, 2025, which is the day after the deadline to submit an executed TCSA (see the version of PP5-6 that received stakeholder support at the joint August 2024 Transmission Committee Reliability Committee meeting and September 2024 Participants Committee, which, among other updates, contains model acceptance testing (MAT) requirements in a new PP5-6 Appendix C-2). Note that ISO-NE will perform MAT for project technical data submittals according to the requirements of the future effective Appendix C-2, and will notify ICs of any identified deficiencies. Though not required, all projects entering the TCS are encouraged to provide the model acceptance testing results documentation that meet the requirements of the future effective Appendix C-2 to reduce the likelihood of needing to address deficiencies identified by ISO-NE through its acceptance testing and reviews performed during the TCS.\n\n*PP5-6 Appendix C-1 and C-1A must be provided for each EMT model submitted by the project, including the required attestations. For example, the Original Equipment Manufacturer (OEM) for inverter, the OEM for HVDC or the OEM for Power Plant Control must individually complete Appendix C 1 and C-1A. The IC (not a consultant to the IC) must sign Appendix C-1B for the Appendix C-1 to be considered complete.\n\nQ6: What technical data must ICs include with the fully executed TCS Agreement?\n\nResponse: The scope of the technical data required for a project with its fully executed TCS \nAgreement depends on the status of the project’s submitted technical data before the TCS \nAgreement is submitted. \nThere are three cases to consider: \n1. Initial Submittal – The IC never submitted any technical data for the project prior to ISO-NE \nissuing TCS Agreements. In other words, the technical data provided by the IC with an \nexecuted TCS Agreement is the first time the IC provides Attachment A and A-1 technical \ndata. \n2. Revised Submittal – The IC submitted the required technical data (i.e., Attachment A and \nA-1 technical data) for the project prior to ISO-NE issuing TCS Agreements, and some or all \nthe previously provided technical data requires revision, or the IC submitted some, but not \nall, of the project’s technical data prior to ISO-NE issuing TCS Agreements. \n3. Unchanged Submittal - The IC submitted the required technical data (i.e., Attachment A \nand A-1 technical data) for the project prior to ISO-NE issuing TCSAs, and none of the \npreviously provided technical data requires revision. \nSubmittal Type Required Technical Data \nSubmittal \n\n| Submittal Type Required Technical Data | Action Required Submittal |\n| --- | --- |\n| Initial Submittal Complete technical data | package |\n| Revised Submittal Revised or missing technical | data only |\n\n| Action Required | | | |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| • Provide all technical data as • Complete Appendix C-1 and | required in Appendix 1 and all information required under its attachments of Schedule 22/23/25 required attestations in C-1A and C-1B in PP5-6 for submitted electromagnetic (EMT) PSCAD models |  Completed Appendix C  Only one Appendix C-1B | 1 and attested C-1A are required for each OEM specific PSCAD model attestation is required for the project |\n| • Provide all revised or missing • Complete Appendix C-1 and | technical data and update Appendix 1 and all information required under its attachments of Schedule 22/23/25 for revised technical data required attestations in C-1A and C-1B in PP5-6 for all revised | | |\n\n| | • Provide written confirmation to | or newly provided EMT PSCAD models IRTT that all other previously submitted technical data remains applicable to the project Include file name ",
